<h1 class="jazz-page-title">Tables</h1>

<p>
A Table component displays tabular data in a two-dimensional table comprised of rows and columns of cells containing data.
</p>

{{ example("/components/tables/tables-example1", "Demonstration", "code-panel-demo") }}

<h3>Best Practices</h3>

<ul>
    <li>Tables should be used for presenting data, not for layout.</li>
    <li>Cells should contain a single value.</li>
    <li>Columns and rows should have an appropriately defined header (<span class="code">th</span>).  Some screen readers will classify a table as a “presentation” table if there are no table headers in the first row.</li>
    <li>Column and row headers must accurately describe the data in those columns/rows.</li>
    <li>Consider row highlighting (even/odd and/or hover) when there are many columns in a row or when the row stretches across a wider screen.</li>
    <li>Provide the ability to filter and sort large data sets.</li>
    <li>Use pagination when data sets are very large and viewing the entire data set at once is not necessary.</li>
    <li>Avoid nesting tables.</li>
    <li>Avoid complex tables with multiple levels of headings.  Instead, strive for a simpler table structure.</li>
    <li>Right-align numeric values where alignment of the decimal places is useful for interpreting the data (i.e. money).  If alignment of the decimal places is useful, be sure that all numbers in that column have the same number of decimal places.</li>
    <li>Consider utilizing a caption within your HTML table structure to provide a description of the table contents.  If there is no need to visually display the caption, it may still be useful for assistive devices.</li>
    <li>Use thead, tfoot, and tbody to properly identify the structure in your table.  This is useful for optimizing printed output for tables.</li>
    <li>As a general rule, it is safest to always use the “scope” attribute on headers.  Although simple tables may not require use of the “scope” attribute, always including it eliminates the need to decide on when the attribute is necessary.</li>
</ul>

